quran[17]{c,v,t,f}:
  52,15,"Is this magic, or do you<sup>pl </sup>not see?"
  52,16,"Roast in it, and be patient or be impatient—it is the same for you<sup>pl </sup>; indeed, you are only being repaid for what you used to do.”"
  52,17,"Indeed, the mindful<i>(of God) </i>are in Gardens and bliss,"
  52,18,"enjoying what their Lord has brought them, and their Lord has shielded them from the punishment of purgatory."
  52,19,"“Eat and drink pleasantly on account of what you<sup>pl </sup>used to do.”"
  52,20,"Relaxing on luxurious furnishings, and We coupled them with spouses with lovely wide eyes."
  52,21,"And those who attained faith and whose offspring{1}followed themin faith—We have united{2}them with theiroffspring{3}, and We have not deprived them of anything of their work; every person is in pledge for what<i>(deeds) </i>he has earned.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Ibn Amer and Ya’qub read it as: “…and whose offspring(s) followed them…” Abu Amr read it as: “And those who attained faith and whom We followed (with) their offspring(s) in faith…”],footnotes:2:[Frequently, the Qur’an addresses the events of the Hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.],footnotes:3:[Qira’at: Nafie’, Abu Amr, Ibn Amer, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…their offspring(s)…”]
  52,22,"And We have supplied them with fruit and meat such as they desire."
  52,23,"They exchange therein a cup which does not lead to any idle talk or recrimination."
  52,24,"And serving them are youths like nestled pearls."
  52,25,"And they approached one another, inquiring."
  52,26,"They said, “When we were still with our families{1}we used to live in fear{2},",footnotes:1:[During their life on earth.],footnotes:2:[Fear of falling into sin.]
  52,27,"so Allah has conferred favor upon us and has shielded us from the punishment of the Scorching Fire."
  52,28,"Indeed, before this we used to pray to Him; indeed ,{1} He is the Fulfiller of promises, the Bestower of mercy.”",footnotes:1:Qira’at: Nafie’, Al-Kesa’i and Abu Ja’far read it as: “…to Him, for He is…”
  52,29,"So remind, for you<sup>sg </sup>are neither a soothsayer nor a madman."
  52,30,"Or do they say, “A poet{1}for whom we await a calamity of time”?",footnotes:1:Some pagans claimed that Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was a poet who authored the Qur’an.
  52,31,"Say<sup>sg </sup>, “Go on awaiting, for I am with you<sup>pl </sup>among those awaiting.”"
